I drove a 1995 Jeep Cherokee from 2004-2011. (She should have been put out of her misery long before that, to say the least.) I was used to going in to mechanics and coming out with a $2500 estimate. One garage employee once told me, "...Basically, after looking at your car, what we suggest...well, this car just shouldn't be on the road." I now have a new (well, new to me) vehicle, that was given pristine love and attention, probably by some dear old woman who maybe drove it 20 miles a week. I'm not the best at car maintenance (every boyfriend I have ends up chewing me out over letting a chip slowly destroy my windshield or the fact that my tires are balder than Mr. Clean), but I've taken decent care of this one. However, my brakes started sounding bad, I took my car in last July somewhere in Tempe, and it turned out there was a bigger issue was going on and I couldn't afford to get both my brakes and said issue fixed at once. Brakes were at 40% and could wait, the mechanic said.  I called Meineke on Thursday, after seeing some good reviews here on Yelp and finally having reached the terrified point regarding the sounds my brakes were making. Yes, at the time I was wishing I could have gone to one of the independent places reviewed on here (there were several nearby with great reviews re: service quality and price), but none of them were open Saturdays and my brakes (along with an oil change) drastically needed to be taken care of. Friendly guy answered the phone and I was surprised to find out they accepted appointments on Saturdays for brakes. A lot of bigger places don't do that, it's just a "show up and hope we can get you in with all these other poor unfortunate souls". I made an appointment for first thing in the morning.   Showed up today, and Mary was at their front desk. SUPER nice, SUPER friendly, and definitely more of a morning person than me. I explained that I needed my brakes done and an oil change, dropped my car off, and my ride and I headed back to my apartment. I got a call 30 minutes later, and my heart instantly began pounding. In my past Jeep days, this has always been the time when the service advisor tells me, ever so nicely, that my car is a gigantic piece of crap, and why do I still own it, and how has it not lit on fire on the freeway yet and tell you what, I know a guy who can make sure it disappears and is found torched in Mexico a month later. Mary said the brakes obviously needed work, and my front rotors DID need to be replaced (the car is at 103,000 miles and the rotors had not been replaced in quite some time so I was not entirely shocked), however the back brakes were just fine. Of course, my air filter was dirty (I know this is usually something car places usually tell everyone, but I am pretty sure mine has not been changed since I bought the car so I'll take her word for it), and there were some other minor issues she recommended getting taken care of soon, but not necessarily today (mostly my fluids needing to be flushed). She was not pushy in the LEAST about the other issues and gave me the quote for the brakes, oil change, filter replacement and fluid replacement. It was half as much as what I had put aside for the repairs. Granted, I did expect both front and rear would need to be done, and I also made a paranoid transfer to my savings account prior, expecting the worst, but still. I looked online for the average cost of front brake work and rotor replacement for my car model, and the price I was given was just under what most websites had estimated. I breathed a huge sigh of relief and Mary said she'd call me when my car was finished. They ended up getting the job done in about an HOUR total. I was pretty amazed. I know brake work is relatively simple in comparison to bigger jobs, but still, most places still make you wait around for three hours or so regardless. Paid for the repairs, and drove my car home, sans horrific attention-whore brake noises and grinding. I'll see how my car feels over the next few days, but so far I am way more impressed by this place than I had anticipated!

